## 4. Brand-specific pages

You can either:

- have 5 different dashboards (`BrandAHomePage`, `BrandBHomePage`…), **or**
- have one widget and switch inside using `switch (brand)`.

Example with one widget per tab but switching brand inside:

```dart
class _BrandHomePage extends ConsumerWidget {
  final Brand brand;
  const _BrandHomePage({required this.brand});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context, WidgetRef ref) {
    final asyncData = ref.watch(brandDataProvider(brand)); // auto reload per brand

    return asyncData.when(
      data: (data) {
        switch (brand) {
          case Brand.a:
            return Center(child: Text('Home A\n$data'));
          case Brand.b:
            return Center(child: Text('Home B\n$data'));
          case Brand.c:
            return Center(child: Text('Home C\n$data'));
          case Brand.d:
            return Center(child: Text('Home D\n$data'));
          case Brand.e:
            return Center(child: Text('Home E\n$data'));
        }
      },
      loading: () => const Center(child: CircularProgressIndicator()),
      error: (e, _) => Center(child: Text('Error: $e')),
    );
  }
}
```

Repeat similar pattern for `_BrandOrderPage`, `_BrandScanPage`, etc.

---

## How the “reload” happens

- When user taps a brand in the drawer:
  - `selectedBrandProvider` changes → `DashboardShell` rebuilds.
  - Any provider **depending on `Brand`** (like `brandDataProvider(brand)`) will automatically fetch new data.
- If you need a hard reset of some providers, use `ref.invalidate(yourProvider)` inside the `onTap`.

---

If you paste this structure into your project, you can gradually replace the `Center(Text(...))` parts with your real UI from `Main.dart`, `B.dart`, etc., either by:
- moving that code into widgets and importing them here, or  
- calling those widgets from `_buildBody` depending on `brand`.

Gotcha — so:

- Bottom navigation is **global** (same 5 tabs for all brands)  
- Only **Home tab’s content** should change when user picks a brand in the drawer.

Perfect, that’s actually simpler. You just:

1. Store the selected brand in a provider.
2. Make the *Home* tab listen to that provider and show a different widget per brand.
3. Other tabs ignore the brand completely.

---

