Nice — you’re almost there. Two common bugs in your snippet:

1. You call the method list like a property: `_buildScreens[_bottomNavIndex]` — it must be `_buildScreens()[_bottomNavIndex]` (or build the list once and index it).  
2. You use `ref.read(brandProvider)` inside `_page()` — that won’t rebuild the UI when the brand changes. Prefer `ref.watch(...)` (or pass `brand` into `_page`) and avoid `!` where possible.

I also suggest using `IndexedStack` to **preserve each tab's state** (so `HomeMainUI()` won't rebuild / lose scroll position when you switch tabs).

Below is a clean, corrected version that fixes those issues and is Riverpod-friendly:

```dart
class MainDashboardUI extends ConsumerStatefulWidget {
  const MainDashboardUI({super.key});

  @override
  ConsumerState<MainDashboardUI> createState() => _MainDashboardUIState();
}

class _MainDashboardUIState extends ConsumerState<MainDashboardUI> {
  int _bottomNavIndex = 0;

  List<Widget> _buildScreens(Brand brand) {
    // pass brand into pages that need it so they rebuild when brand changes
    return [
      const HomeMainUI(),
      _page("Order", brand),
      _page("Scan QR", brand),
      _page("Waiting List", brand),
      _page("Inbox", brand),
    ];
  }

  Widget _page(String title, Brand brand) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        backgroundColor: brand.colors.primary,
        foregroundColor: brand.colors.secondary,
        title: Text(title),
      ),
      body: Center(child: Text(title)), // replace with actual content
    );
  }

  BottomNavigationBar _bottomNavigationBar(Brand brand) {
    return BottomNavigationBar(
      currentIndex: _bottomNavIndex,
      onTap: (index) => setState(() => _bottomNavIndex = index),
      selectedItemColor: brand.colors.primary,
      unselectedItemColor: brand.colors.secondary,
      items: const [
        BottomNavigationBarItem(icon: Icon(Icons.home), label: "Home"),
        BottomNavigationBarItem(icon: Icon(Icons.shopping_bag), label: "Order"),
        BottomNavigationBarItem(icon: Icon(Icons.qr_code), label: "Scan"),
        BottomNavigationBarItem(icon: Icon(Icons.list_alt), label: "Waiting"),
        BottomNavigationBarItem(icon: Icon(Icons.notifications), label: "Inbox"),
      ],
    );
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    // watch so UI updates if brand changes
    final brand = ref.watch(brandProvider)!; // if provider can be null handle safely

    final screens = _buildScreens(brand);

    return Scaffold(
      // use IndexedStack to preserve state of each tab
      body: IndexedStack(
        index: _bottomNavIndex,
        children: screens,
      ),
      bottomNavigationBar: _bottomNavigationBar(brand),
    );
  }
}
```

### Notes / extras
- If `brandProvider` can be `null`, prefer `ref.watch(brandProvider)` and show a loading/fallback UI instead of using `!`.  
- If you want to keep the tabs lightweight and still recreate them on each selection, you can use `body: screens[_bottomNavIndex]` instead of `IndexedStack`.  
- To move navigation state out of the widget, make `_bottomNavIndex` managed by a `StateProvider<int>` or `StateNotifier` (useful when multiple widgets need to read/change the active tab).

