Nice — I see the issues. Your current snippet mixes a `Stream`-based refresh with a `authCoreNotifier` variable that doesn’t exist in that scope. The fix is to:

- **Use `ref.read(...)` inside `redirect`** to get the latest auth/brand state (don’t rely on a captured/local notifier variable that isn’t defined).  
- **Provide a proper `Stream` to `GoRouterRefreshStream`** (for example `authStateStream`).  
- Optionally **merge other streams** (brand changes) if you want router refresh on brand switch — or use a small `RouterNotifier` (ChangeNotifier) that listens to multiple providers (recommended if you need multi-provider refresh).

Below are two complete, ready-to-paste solutions.

---

# Option A — Keep `GoRouterRefreshStream(authStream)` (simple)

Use this if you already have an `authStateStream` from your auth provider and only need router refresh when auth changes.

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:flutter_riverpod/flutter_riverpod.dart';
import 'package:go_router/go_router.dart';
import '../core/services/brand.s.dart';
import '/routers/auth_router/auth.r.dart';
import '/routers/brand_router/brand.r.dart';
import '../core/auth/auth.c.dart';

class AppRouter {
  AppRouter._();

  /// Create a GoRouter which refreshes when auth state stream emits.
  static GoRouter createRouter(WidgetRef ref) {
    // get the auth service / notifier which exposes the stream
    final authService = ref.read(authCoreProvider);
    final authStream = authService.authStateStream;

    return GoRouter(
      initialLocation: '/',
      debugLogDiagnostics: true,
      // refresh when authStream emits
      refreshListenable: GoRouterRefreshStream(authStream),
      redirect: (context, state) {
        // inside redirect, read the providers for the latest state
        final auth = ref.read(authCoreProvider);
        final bool loggedIn = auth.isLoggedIn;

        final bool onLoginPage = state.matchedLocation == '/login';
        final bool onRoot = state.matchedLocation == '/';

        final brand = ref.read(brandProvider);

        // your redirect logic (kept semantics of your original example)
        if (!loggedIn && !onLoginPage) {
          return '/main';
        }

        if (loggedIn && (onLoginPage || onRoot)) {
          if (brand != null) {
            return '/main';
          }

          return '/main';
        }

        return null;
      },
      routes: [...authRoutes, ...brandRoutes],
      errorBuilder: (context, state) {
        return Scaffold(
          appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('404')),
          body: Center(child: Text('Halaman tidak ditemukan: ${state.error}')),
        );
      },
    );
  }
}
```

**Notes**
- `ref.read(authCoreProvider)` must return an object exposing `authStateStream` and `isLoggedIn`. If those names differ in your code, substitute accordingly.
- `GoRouterRefreshStream` will cause GoRouter to call `redirect` whenever `authStream` emits — that’s why `redirect` uses `ref.read(...)` to read the current provider values.
- This only refreshes on auth events. If you also want the router to refresh when `brandProvider` changes, see Option B.

---

# Option B — Recommended for multiple triggers: `RouterNotifier` (ChangeNotifier + `ref.listen`)

Create a small `RouterNotifier` that listens to multiple providers (auth, brand, etc.) and calls `notifyListeners()` when any of them change. This is the cleanest when redirects depend on multiple providers.

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:flutter_riverpod/flutter_riverpod.dart';
import 'package:go_router/go_router.dart';
import '../core/services/brand.s.dart';
import '/routers/auth_router/auth.r.dart';
import '/routers/brand_router/brand.r.dart';
import '../core/auth/auth.c.dart';

/// A tiny ChangeNotifier that listens to providers and notifies GoRouter.
class RouterNotifier extends ChangeNotifier {
  RouterNotifier(WidgetRef ref) : _ref = ref {
    // listen auth provider
    _ref.listen(authCoreProvider, (_, __) => notifyListeners());
    // listen brand provider
    _ref.listen<BrandModel?>(brandProvider, (_, __) => notifyListeners());
    // add more listeners here if needed (role, permissions, etc.)
  }

  final WidgetRef _ref;
}

class AppRouter {
  AppRouter._();

  static GoRouter createRouter(WidgetRef ref) {
    final routerNotifier = RouterNotifier(ref);

    return GoRouter(
      initialLocation: '/',
      debugLogDiagnostics: true,
      refreshListenable: routerNotifier,
      redirect: (context, state) {
        // read the latest values on each redirect call
        final auth = ref.read(authCoreProvider);
        final bool loggedIn = auth.isLoggedIn;

        final bool onLoginPage = state.matchedLocation == '/login';
        final bool onRoot = state.matchedLocation == '/';

        final brand = ref.read(brandProvider);

        if (!loggedIn && !onLoginPage) {
          return '/main';
        }

        if (loggedIn && (onLoginPage || onRoot)) {
          if (brand != null) {
            return '/main';
          }
          return '/main';
        }

        return null;
      },
      routes: [...authRoutes, ...brandRoutes],
      errorBuilder: (context, state) {
        return Scaffold(
          appBar: AppBar(title: const Text('404')),
          body: Center(child: Text('Halaman tidak ditemukan: ${state.error}')),
        );
      },
    );
  }
}
```

**Why this is often better**
- `RouterNotifier` can listen to as many providers as you need (auth, brand, roles, feature flags) and will call `notifyListeners()` when any change — `GoRouter` will then re-run `redirect` so you can handle navigation changes in one place.
- You avoid creating/managing merged streams and the complexity of ensuring stream lifecycles/cancellations are correct.

---

# Quick debugging checklist if redirects still misbehave
- Ensure your providers actually change identity (i.e., they update the state instance). If you mutate an object in-place, `ref.listen`/streams may not fire — use immutable state updates.
- Use `debugPrint()` inside `redirect`/listeners to ensure the methods are triggered.
- Make sure `RouterNotifier` instance lives long enough — creating it inside `createRouter` and passing to `GoRouter.refreshListenable` is correct (GoRouter holds the reference).
- Avoid `ref.watch` inside `redirect` — use `ref.read` inside `redirect` and let the `refreshListenable`/`RouterNotifier` drive when `redirect` is re-evaluated.

