Great — here are a few solid, practical ways to add analytics to your GoRouter navigation (Firebase or any analytics backend). I’ll show both a simple out-of-the-box method (use a `NavigatorObserver`) and a more explicit approach (custom observer that logs screen_view with route name + params). Both work with `MaterialApp.router` + `GoRouter`.

Pick one and paste it into your app.

---

## Option A — Quick: use a `NavigatorObserver` (recommended for Firebase)
If you use Firebase Analytics, you can attach an observer to your `MaterialApp.router`. In your `MyApp.build()` (a `ConsumerWidget`) create the analytics instance and pass an observer to `navigatorObservers`.

```dart
// analytics_service.dart
import 'package:firebase_analytics/firebase_analytics.dart';

class AnalyticsService {
  AnalyticsService(this._analytics);
  final FirebaseAnalytics _analytics;

  Future<void> logScreenView({required String screenName}) async {
    await _analytics.logScreenView(screenName: screenName);
  }

  Future<void> logEvent(String name, {Map<String, Object?>? params}) async {
    await _analytics.logEvent(name: name, parameters: params);
  }
}
```

```dart
// main.dart (or where you build the app)
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:flutter_riverpod/flutter_riverpod.dart';
import 'package:firebase_analytics/firebase_analytics.dart';
import 'analytics_service.dart';
import 'routers/app_router.dart';

final analyticsProvider = Provider<AnalyticsService>((ref) {
  return AnalyticsService(FirebaseAnalytics.instance);
});

class MyApp extends ConsumerWidget {
  const MyApp({super.key});
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context, WidgetRef ref) {
    final router = AppRouter.createRouter(ref);
    final analytics = ref.read(analyticsProvider);

    // Firebase provides FirebaseAnalyticsObserver but it's okay to use custom
    // or use FirebaseAnalyticsObserver(firebaseAnalytics: FirebaseAnalytics.instance)
    final observers = <NavigatorObserver>[
      FirebaseAnalyticsObserver(analytics: FirebaseAnalytics.instance),
    ];

    return MaterialApp.router(
      routerConfig: router,
      title: 'MyApp',
      navigatorObservers: observers,
    );
  }
}
```

**Notes**
- Make sure each `GoRoute` has a `name:` so the observer can report meaningful names.
- The Firebase-provided observer will automatically log screen views for navigation events.

---

## Option B — Explicit: custom `NavigatorObserver` (works for any analytics)
If you want control (send route params, filter routes, debounce, etc.), create a custom observer that calls your `AnalyticsService`. Then add it in `MaterialApp.router`.

```dart
// analytics_route_observer.dart
import 'package:flutter/widgets.dart';
import 'analytics_service.dart';

class AnalyticsRouteObserver extends NavigatorObserver {
  AnalyticsRouteObserver(this._analytics);

  final AnalyticsService _analytics;

  String _routeNameFrom(Route<dynamic>? route) {
    if (route == null) return 'unknown';
    final name = route.settings.name;
    return name ?? route.toString();
  }

  @override
  void didPush(Route route, Route? previousRoute) {
    final name = _routeNameFrom(route);
    _analytics.logScreenView(screenName: name);
    super.didPush(route, previousRoute);
  }

  @override
  void didReplace({Route? newRoute, Route? oldRoute}) {
    final name = _routeNameFrom(newRoute);
    _analytics.logScreenView(screenName: name);
    super.didReplace(newRoute: newRoute, oldRoute: oldRoute);
  }

  @override
  void didPop(Route route, Route? previousRoute) {
    final name = _routeNameFrom(previousRoute);
    if (name != 'unknown') _analytics.logScreenView(screenName: name);
    super.didPop(route, previousRoute);
  }
}
```

Then provide it in your app:

```dart
// in MyApp.build (ConsumerWidget)
final analytics = ref.read(analyticsProvider);
final observers = <NavigatorObserver>[AnalyticsRouteObserver(analytics)];

return MaterialApp.router(
  routerConfig: router,
  navigatorObservers: observers,
);
```

**Advantages**
- Full control over what you log and when.
- Can log parameters: inspect `route.settings.arguments` or the `GoRouterState` before calling `context.go()`.

---

## Option C — Hook into GoRouter redirects / RouterNotifier (Riverpod-friendly)
If you already use a `RouterNotifier` that `ref.listen`es providers, you can call analytics from there when navigation-relevant providers change. Example: when brand changes, log an event:

```dart
// inside RouterNotifier._notifyIfChanged() after detecting brand change:
if (_lastBrandId != brand?.id) {
  _ref.read(analyticsProvider).logEvent('brand_changed', params: {'brand_id': brand?.id});
}
```

But note: this is for *events caused by state changes*, not generic screen_view events. For screen views prefer a `NavigatorObserver`.

---

## Extra tips / best practices
- Give routes stable `name:` values in your GoRouter route definitions. Use `name` instead of relying on the long path string.
- Avoid logging too many events (debounce rapid navigation).
- If you want to capture query params or dynamic segments, inspect `Route.settings.name` or use `onGenerateRoute` style logic — with `go_router` you can access `GoRouterState` inside builders and log there too.
- For privacy, strip PII before logging.
- Test in dev: use `debugPrint` in your observer to verify events before sending to analytics.

---

## Example: named GoRoute + observer integration
```dart
final routes = [
  GoRoute(
    path: '/',
    name: 'home',
    builder: (context, state) => const HomePage(),
  ),
  GoRoute(
    path: '/product/:id',
    name: 'product',
    builder: (context, state) {
      final id = state.params['id']!;
      // optionally log here too:
      // ref.read(analyticsProvider).logEvent('open_product', params: {'id': id});
      return ProductPage(id: id);
    },
  ),
];
```

Then the `NavigatorObserver` will pick up those route `name`s when navigation happens.

