## 1. Is this structure good for 3 devs?

Your structure (simplified):

```text
lib
  brands/
    sushitei/
      dashboard/ui/widgets
    hokkaidoya/
      dashboard/ui/widgets
  config/
  core/
  models/
  routers/
  app.dart
  main.dart
```

### ✅ Pros for teamwork

- Clear separation:
  - `core`, `config`, `api`, `auth` are shared.
  - Each brand lives in `brands/<brand_name>/...`
- It’s easy to split work:
  - Dev A: `core`, `api`, `auth`, `routers`
  - Dev B: Brand 1 (Sushitei)
  - Dev C: Brand 2 (Hokkaidoya) + new brands

So yes, it *can* work well for 3 people.

### ⚠️ But watch out for:

1. **Duplication**  
   If every brand has its own dashboard widgets that are 90% the same, you’ll copy-paste a lot.

   Example:
   ```text
   brands/sushitei/dashboard/ui/sushitei.d.ui.dart
   brands/hokkaidoya/dashboard/ui/hokkaidoya.d.ui.dart
   ```
   If they look similar, you probably want a **shared dashboard feature** with small brand overrides.

2. **Router explosion**
   ```text
   routers/brand_router/sushitei.r.dart
   routers/brand_router/hokkaidoya.r.dart
   ```
   If every brand has its own router file, managing routes gets painful when you have 5+ brands.

3. **Tight coupling**
   If brand files import stuff directly from random places in `core` and `config`, refactoring will hurt.

---

## 2. How to make it truly multi-brand

Let’s assume you want **one codebase** that supports **many brands** (white-label style).  
General idea:

> Shared core + shared features, with **BrandConfig** that decides:
> - theme
> - logos
> - API base URL
> - brand-specific dashboard widget
> - maybe brand-specific routes

### 2.1. Define a Brand model & config

You already have `models/brand.m.dart`. Use it as a central source of truth.

**`brand.m.dart`**:

```dart
enum BrandType {
  sushitei,
  hokkaidoya,
  // etc...
}

class BrandConfig {
  final BrandType type;
  final String code;       // "sushitei"
  final String displayName;
  final String apiBaseUrl;
  final ThemeData theme;
  final Widget Function() dashboardBuilder;

  const BrandConfig({
    required this.type,
    required this.code,
    required this.displayName,
    required this.apiBaseUrl,
    required this.theme,
    required this.dashboardBuilder,
  });
}
```

**`config/app.config.dart`**:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import '../models/brand.m.dart';
import '../brands/sushitei/dashboard/ui/sushitei.d.ui.dart';
import '../brands/hokkaidoya/dashboard/ui/hokkaidoya.d.ui.dart';

final Map<BrandType, BrandConfig> kBrandConfigs = {
  BrandType.sushitei: BrandConfig(
    type: BrandType.sushitei,
    code: 'sushitei',
    displayName: 'Sushitei',
    apiBaseUrl: 'https://api.sushitei.com',
    theme: ThemeData(
      // Sushitei theme here
    ),
    dashboardBuilder: () => SushiteiDashboardScreen(),
  ),
  BrandType.hokkaidoya: BrandConfig(
    type: BrandType.hokkaidoya,
    code: 'hokkaidoya',
    displayName: 'Hokkaidoya',
    apiBaseUrl: 'https://api.hokkaidoya.com',
    theme: ThemeData(
      // Hokkaidoya theme here
    ),
    dashboardBuilder: () => HokkaidoyaDashboardScreen(),
  ),
};
```

Now **all brand-specific choices** are centralized.

---

### 2.2. Brand service: who is the current brand?

In `core/services/brand.s.dart`:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/foundation.dart';
import '../../models/brand.m.dart';
import '../../config/app.config.dart';

class BrandService extends ChangeNotifier {
  BrandType _currentBrand = BrandType.sushitei;

  BrandType get currentBrand => _currentBrand;
  BrandConfig get config => kBrandConfigs[_currentBrand]!;

  void setBrand(BrandType brand) {
    if (_currentBrand == brand) return;
    _currentBrand = brand;
    notifyListeners();
  }
}
```

You can expose this via Provider, Riverpod, GetIt, etc.

---

### 2.3. main.dart: start app with a brand

Basic example using `BrandType`:

```dart
void main() {
  const brand = BrandType.sushitei; // or set from --dart-define / env

  runApp(MyApp(initialBrand: brand));
}

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  final BrandType initialBrand;

  const MyApp({super.key, required this.initialBrand});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final brandService = BrandService();
    brandService.setBrand(initialBrand);

    return ChangeNotifierProvider.value(
      value: brandService,
      child: Consumer<BrandService>(
        builder: (context, brand, _) {
          final config = brand.config;

          return MaterialApp.router(
            title: config.displayName,
            theme: config.theme,
            routerConfig: createAppRouter(brand),
          );
        },
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

> If you want **multiple app binaries** (one per brand), you can create:
>
> - `main_sushitei.dart` → `BrandType.sushitei`
> - `main_hokkaidoya.dart` → `BrandType.hokkaidoya`  
> and use Flutter flavors / different bundle ids.

---

### 2.4. Router: multi-brand without chaos

Instead of separate routers for each brand:

```text
routers/
  app.router.dart
  auth_router/auth.r.dart
  brand_router/brand.r.dart   <-- single entry point
```

In `brand.r.dart`:

```dart
import 'package:flutter/widgets.dart';
import '../../core/services/brand.s.dart';
import '../../config/app.config.dart';

Route<dynamic>? onGenerateBrandRoute(RouteSettings settings, BrandService brand) {
  final config = brand.config;

  switch (settings.name) {
    case '/dashboard':
      return MaterialPageRoute(builder: (_) => config.dashboardBuilder());
    // Add more brand-aware routes here if needed.
  }

  return null;
}
```

In `app.router.dart`, you wire it:

```dart
Route<dynamic>? onGenerateRoute(RouteSettings settings, BrandService brand) {
  // Routes that are same for all brands
  switch (settings.name) {
    case '/login':
      return MaterialPageRoute(builder: (_) => const LoginScreen());
  }

  // Fallback to brand-specific routes
  return onGenerateBrandRoute(settings, brand);
}
```

So you keep routing logic **central**, but the actual widget is **brand-specific** via `BrandConfig`.

---

### 2.5. Shared vs per-brand UI

Your current structure:

```text
brands/
  sushitei/dashboard/ui/...
  hokkaidoya/dashboard/ui/...
```

Suggestion:

- Put **shared widgets** into `core/ui` or `features/dashboard/ui`.
- Only override what *really* differs per brand.

Example:

```text
lib/
  features/
    dashboard/
      ui/
        dashboard_base.dart      // common layout, logic
  brands/
    sushitei/
      dashboard/
        ui/sushitei_dashboard.dart  // extends/uses dashboard_base
    hokkaidoya/
      dashboard/
        ui/hokkaidoya_dashboard.dart
```

`dashboard_base.dart`:

```dart
class BaseDashboard extends StatelessWidget {
  final String title;
  final List<Widget> sections;

  const BaseDashboard({
    super.key,
    required this.title,
    required this.sections,
  });

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(title: Text(title)),
      body: ListView(children: sections),
    );
  }
}
```

Sushitei dashboard:

```dart
class SushiteiDashboardScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return BaseDashboard(
      title: 'Sushitei Dashboard',
      sections: [
        // Sushitei-specific sections here.
      ],
    );
  }
}
```

